03885nam a22005295i 9780520921429DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209214297 a10.1525/97805209214292doi  a(DE-B1597)649135  a(OCoLC)1419789606  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0190002bisacsh1 aCollins, Arthur, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPossible Experience :bUnderstanding Kant's Critique of Pure Reason /cArthur Collins; ed. by Arthur Collins. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (219 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Texts and Abbreviations -- t1. Kant and the Cartesian Philosophy of Mind -- t2. Subjectivism versus Idealism -- t3. Idealism and Transcendental Idealism -- t4. Are Things-in-Themselves Noumena? -- t5. The Concept of Representation -- t6. "Space Is in Us" -- t7. Outer Causes of Perception -- t8. Kant Not a Foundationalist -- t9. The "How-Possible" Questions -- t10. The "Clue" for Finding the Categories -- t11. The Parallelism of Inner and Outer Sense -- t12 . The Subject of Experience -- t13. How Representations Make Objects Possible -- t14. Objects and Empirical Realism -- t15. The Idealistic Understanding of Kant's Theoretical Philosophy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArthur Collins's succinct, revisionist exposition of Kant's Critique of Pure Reason brings a new clarity to this notoriously difficult text. Until recently most readers, ascribing broadly Cartesian assumptions to Kant, have concluded that the Critique advances an idealist philosophy, because Kant calls it "transcendental idealism" and because the work abounds in apparent confirmations of that interpretation.Collins maintains not only that this reading of Kant is false but also that it conceals Kant's real achievements. To counter it, he addresses the themes and passages in the Critique that seem to require an idealist thesis and shows how they may be better understood without ascribing any idealist philosophy to Kant. His account coheres with Kant's explicit "refutations" of idealism, it fits Kant's rejection of the imputation of idealism to him by early critics and readers, and it validates Kant's contention that the second edition of the Critique changes the expression but not the doctrine of the first.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aCollins, Arthur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021499640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092142940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921429/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles